sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, gender, previous_volunteer, number_volunteer_r, attendance and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + gender + previous_volunteer + number_volunteer_r + attendance + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.31) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.18. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, previous_volunteer = yes_beyong_12_month, number_volunteer_r = 0, attendance = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 21.79 (S.E. = 2.34, p < .001, 95% CI [17.21, 26.38]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.03, S.E. = 0.03, p = 0.288, 95% CI [-0.09, 0.03]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.51, 0.15])
  • The effect of gender [male] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.67, S.E. = 1.01, p = 0.506, 95% CI [-1.31, 2.65]; Std. beta = 0.28, 95% CI [-0.55, 1.11])
  • The effect of previous volunteer [yes_within_12_month] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.71, S.E. = 0.80, p = 0.371, 95% CI [-0.85, 2.28]; Std. beta = 0.30, 95% CI [-0.36, 0.95])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.61, S.E. = 0.50, p = 0.214, 95% CI [-0.36, 1.59]; Std. beta = 0.23, 95% CI [-0.13, 0.59])
  • The effect of attendance is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.36, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.361, 95% CI [-1.15, 0.42]; Std. beta = -0.15, 95% CI [-0.48, 0.18])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.49, S.E. = 0.82, p = 0.547, 95% CI [-1.11, 2.10]; Std. beta = 0.21, 95% CI [-0.47, 0.88])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
